            <pb n="4" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1" xml:lang="eng">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Vaccination.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The dispute on the efficacy of vacci-<lb break="no"/>nation as a preservative from one of the most afflict-<lb break="no"/>ing and dangerous disorders to which the human<lb break="yes"/>frame is subject, has, perhaps, nearly subsided.<lb break="yes"/>Obstinacy, however, still clings to error, and preju-<lb break="no"/>dice and false reasoning have not entirely left the<lb break="yes"/>field. The following statement, given on the autho-<lb break="no"/>rity of <persName key="humboldt_av">Humbolt</persName>, will therefore be read with interest.<lb break="yes"/>It offers another strong point of evidence in favour<lb break="yes"/>of the Jennerian application of the vaccine virus;<lb break="yes"/>because it shews that the same fact had been observed<lb break="yes"/>in the <placeName key="anden">Andes</placeName> as in the meadows in England, and pre-<lb break="no"/>cisely the same inference drawn from it.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;In 1802, the small pox prevailed on the coast<lb break="yes"/>of the South Sea. At this time it was discovered<lb break="yes"/>that the beneficial effect of vaccination had been long<lb break="yes"/>known to the country people among the Peruvian<lb break="yes"/>
                    <placeName key="anden">Andes</placeName>. A negro slave had been inoculated for the<lb break="yes"/>small-pox, in the house of the Marquis de Vallam-<lb break="no"/>broso, who shewed no <choice>
                        <sic>symptosm</sic>
                        <corr type="editorial">symptoms</corr>
                    </choice> of disease. They<lb break="yes"/>were going to repeat the inoculation when the young<lb break="yes"/>man told them he was certain of never having the<lb break="yes"/>small pox, because in milking cows in the Cordillera<lb break="yes"/>of the <placeName key="anden">Andes</placeName>, he had a sort of cutaneous eruption,<lb break="yes"/>caused, as the Indian herdsman said, by the contact<lb break="yes"/>of certain tubercles sometimes found on the udders<lb break="yes"/>of cows. Those who have had these eruptions, said<lb break="yes"/>the negro, never take the small-pox. The Africans,<lb break="yes"/>and especially the Indians, display great sagacity in<lb break="yes"/>observing the habits and diseases of the animals with<lb break="yes"/>which they live. We need not, therefore, be sur-<lb break="no" />prised, that on the introduction of horned cattle into<lb break="yes"/>
                    <placeName key="amerika">America</placeName>, the lower people remarked, that the pus-<lb break="no"/>tules on the udders of cows communicated to the<lb break="yes"/>herdsmen a sort of benignant small-pox, and that<lb break="yes" />those once infected were secure from the general<lb break="yes"/>contagion during those epochs when the disease is<lb break="yes"/><choice><sic>epidemical&#x201D;</sic><corr type="editorial">epidemical.&#x201D;</corr></choice></p>
            </div>
